<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Publishers agree code of practice
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
More than three years after the publication of the Sadler inquiry into
cross-media promotion, newspaper and magazine publishers have finally agreed
a code of practice.
Mr Neil Hamilton, the Department of Trade and Industry corporate affairs
minister, announced yesterday publication of a code which has been endorsed
by the main publishing organisations.
One of the recommendations of the report by Mr John Sadler, former deputy
chairman of the John Lewis group and the new chairman of Pearl, the life
insurer, was that newspapers should establish a code covering both editorial
and advertising content.
The code refers to such areas as conditions of supply, non-discriminatory
rates for competitors' advertising and the publication of relevant ownership
links in editorial and advertising.
The Cross-Media Promotion Code was drawn up by the Newspaper Publishers'
Association on behalf of national newspapers, the Newspaper Society
representing local and regional newspapers, and the Periodical Publishers'
Association and their Scottish counterparts. Publications are being
encouraged to publish their own in-house guidelines on the coverage of
competitors.
</TEXT>
