<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Jobless figure at lowest for two years
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The number of people out of work fell for the third consecutive month in all
regions of Britain in April, taking the unemployment rate to its lowest
level for two years.
Unemployment fell by 36,800 in April compared with March, bringing the
seasonally adjusted number of unemployed down to 2.682m, the Department of
Employment yesterday said.
This leaves unemployment running at 9.5 per cent of the total work force -
almost a percentage point lower than last April's rate of 10.4 per cent.
Coming after similar large drops in February and March, the figures also
suggest that unemployment fell by more than 100,000 during the last three
months, at an average monthly rate of 36,000.
Mr David Hunt, employment secretary, yesterday welcomed the figures as
evidence that unemployment was on 'a firm downward trend' at an accelerating
rate.
One of the most significant falls, he said, had occurred in the 18- to
24-year-old age group, where unemployment had dropped by 61,100 in the last
quarter, and by more than 100,000 in the past year. This trend was most
marked among males aged between 20 and 24, with a drop in long term
unemployment of 12 per cent in the last year. A drop in the number of young
unemployed men is usually regarded by economists as a key sign of recovery.
Mr John Prescott, shadow employment secretary, denounced the figures,
claiming they concealed a 'huge army of missing millions' pushed off the
social security register.
'Since January last year the number of unemployed people on benefit has
indeed fallen by 289,000, but that does not mean that they are all finding
work,' he said.
This scepticism was echoed by some City economists, who pointed out that the
drop in unemployment did not appear to be entirely matched by evidence of
new job creation, not least because employment levels in production industry
had actually fallen recently.
Total employment in the manufacturing industries fell by 12,000 during
March, while employment in the energy, water and supply industries was down
by 5,000.
However, this was partly offset by a growth in vacancies and overtime,
analysts added. Seasonally adjusted vacancies at job centres rose by 5,300
to 145,900 in April, taking the number of vacancies to their highest level
since October 1990. Hours worked per week in manufacturing industries rose
to 9.72m in March, nearly 500,000 per week up on the previous month.
As a result, Mr Leo Doyle, economist at Kleinwort Benson, said that most
city analysts were now sufficiently convinced of the underlying downward
trend that they were prepared to discount small doubts about the details.
'I think there is an element of exaggeration in these unemployment figures,
but you can't dismiss them - the trend is clearly down,' Mr Doyle said.
Meanwhile, the number of work stoppages in the 12 months to March fell to
168, the lowest level since the department began keeping records in 1920.
