<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Portillo hopeful on cutting deficit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Government action to reduce the public-sector borrowing requirement should
serve in turn to cut Britain's large current account deficit, Mr Michael
Portillo, chief secretary to the Treasury, said last night, Peter Norman
writes.
But in a speech to the Lombard Association in the City, Mr Portillo warned
that the current-account deficit, which was an estimated Pounds 10.9bn last
year, was unlikely to improve as rapidly as the PSBR, which the government
expects to fall close to zero during the next five years.
In the first public speech about the current account by a Treasury minister
in several years, Mr Portillo said that people 'should not automatically be
alarmed' about whether it is in surplus or deficit. As long as British
investment opportunities continued to look worthwhile, the current-account
deficit could be financed, he said.
</TEXT>
