<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Labour keeps lid on leadership race
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Labour yesterday attempted to clamp down on speculation about the party
leadership by extending a ban on campaigning until after the European
parliament election on June 9.
The shadow cabinet gave unanimous endorsement to demands from Mrs Margaret
Beckett, the deputy leader, for a three-week moratorium on leadership
statements.
The moratorium is intended to stop speculation about the leadership
undermining Labour's campaign for the election, in which the party hopes to
win up to 15 extra seats.
But officials said there would be no sanctions against candidates who break
the rules except 'a great deal of criticism from their colleagues'.
The decision was announced as it emerged that Mr Gordon Brown, one of two
modernist contenders, will make a major speech to the Welsh Labour
conference on Sunday.
Mr Brown, the shadow chancellor, whose unofficial campaign has flagged in
the week since the death of John Smith, the former leader, will be free
under the rules to set out his view of Labour's future.
Labour MPs were sceptical about the prospects of a successful ban on
campaigning. Some said it would simply encourage arms-length electioneering
by supporters.
Mr Tony Blair, shadow home secretary, who was to have addressed the Welsh
conference during its cancelled Saturday session, has declined an invitation
to speak on Sunday.
But he and the two other main contenders - Mr Robin Cook, shadow trade and
industry secretary, and Mr John Prescott, shadow employment secretary - are
free to give interviews as long as they do not announce formally that they
are standing.
Mrs Beckett, a potential leftwing candidate, will be interviewed by Sir
David Frost on BBC television on Sunday.
The problems the party will face in keeping a lid on public campaigning were
underlined by claims that Mr Peter Mandelson, MP for Hartlepool and Labour's
former publicity director, had been campaigning for Mr Blair. The
allegation, levelled by Mr Nigel Griffiths, shadow consumer affairs minister
and a supporter of Mr Brown, was quickly withdrawn after protests from the
shadow chancellor's office.
John Smith will be buried on the Scottish island of Iona on Saturday after a
funeral tomorrow at the church in Edinburgh where he was a regular
worshipper.
Electoral college, Page 11
Observer, Page 23
</TEXT>
