<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Doctors warn of disputes over pay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The National Health Service will face 'unseemly and divisive' local disputes
if proposals to introduce performance-related pay are implemented, the
British Medical Association warned the government yesterday.
Ministers want the NHS to begin moving from central to local pay
determination this year. Following a series of preliminary meetings with
Department of Health officials, the BMA yesterday expressed 'profound
objections' to doctors' national terms and conditions being changed.
BMA leaders say they have been told that, from next April, the Doctors and
Dentists Review Body will recommend only 'exceptionally modest' national
increases, leaving local NHS trusts to award any further rises under
performance related pay schemes.
Dr Sandy Macara, chairman of the BMA council, warned in a letter to Mrs
Virginia Bottomley, health secretary, yesterday that the degree of control
such schemes offered managers would introduce a dangerous principle to the
medical field.
Hospital consultants' first duty was to their patients, but there was a risk
of performance related pay forcing them to comply with a trust's business
needs.
The BMA has told Mrs Bottomley that it is willing to discuss alternative
remuneration structures for doctors, but it objects to being faced with a
'single dogmatic solution'.
The 1991 NHS reforms heralded a move from central pay determination. Many
doctors believe that the existence of national pay and conditions is an
important element in ensuring consistent standards of care across the
country.
</TEXT>
