<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Accounts body presses ahead on disclosure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Accounting Standards Board is considering lobbying the government and
the Stock Exchange in efforts to force greater disclosure of directors'
share options.
The action follows a legal opinion which has scuppered attempts by the board
 -which sets accounting standards - to introduce compulsory additional
information on remuneration.
The board's urgent-issues taskforce yesterday unveiled a diluted set of
voluntary guidelines for companies to highlight the number and value of
share options granted to directors.
It began considering the topic last year at the suggestion of a number of
auditing firms following recommendations for greater disclosure in the
Cadbury report on the financial aspects of corporate governance.
It was planning to introduce a standard with which all companies would have
to comply. This comes as similar tough measures are being debated by the US
Financial Accounting Standards Board.
However, a recent legal opinion obtained by the board said that the wording
of existing legislation does not require additional disclosure unless there
is certainty over the value of the options.
Members of the taskforce are now debating whether to put pressure on the
Department of Trade and Industry to modify the law to force greater
disclosure as part of its review of companies legislation.
They are also considering suggesting to the Stock Exchange that it modifies
the listing requirements for quoted companies in order to boost disclosure.
The taskforce suggests disclosure of the prices that apply to directors'
options overall and to individual directors, together with market price
information at the year-end and at the date of exercise of the options.
A separate abstract published yesterday clarifies the treatment of benefits
used as incentives to encourage companies to sign leases - known as reverse
premiums.
It proposes that these should be spread on a straight-line basis - by the
same amount each year - over the term of the lease, or over the period to
when the rent is first adjusted.
The ruling follows heavy losses reported by Pentos, the speciality retailer,
last year. In the previous year it had included reverse premiums in profits
of Pounds 6.3m. Without these it would have reported losses.
In a third abstract, the taskforce proposes that when a debt instrument
includes a call option that can be exercised only by the issuer, the payment
required on exercise of the option should not form part of the instrument's
finance costs.
</TEXT>
<XX>
