<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Mutual hostility in Gaza pullout
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Middle East has a long way to go before it can expect peaceful
co-existence between Arab and Jew.
Israeli soldiers, trying to complete their military withdrawal from the Gaza
Strip yesterday, spent the last minutes of occupation battling angry
stone-throwing youths. Even as the last military convoy of jeeps sped out of
Gaza City youths lobbed bottles and stones at the Israelis and taunted them
with insults.
The farewell clashes were an important reminder of the violence and
hostility which still characterises Arab-Israeli relations. Palestinian and
Israeli leaders may have signed an interim peace accord but decades of
hatred and suspicion on both sides will take years to overcome.
Although the 14-day transfer of power in Gaza and Jericho has gone smoothly
potential violent flash points are everywhere, particularly in the rest of
the West Bank which will not come under Palestinian control until elections
are held.
There has been tit-for-tat violence in Hebron and in Jericho armed Jewish
religious students threaten conflict with the new Palestinian security
forces by refusing to surrender their weapons or enter the synagogue
unarmed.
The potential for continuing violence remains high because of the very
limited way in which the interim peace agreement meets Palestinian
aspirations. The bulk of Palestinian demands - removal of Jewish settlements
on Arab lands, the right to establish a state, the right of return of all
refugees and, at the least, shared control of Jerusalem - have all been
shelved to a later date.
So long as the 125,000 Jewish settlers, protected by Israeli soldiers,
remain untouched in Gaza and the West Bank extremist groups preaching and
practicing violence will continue to flourish.
'The settlements are a time-bomb in the peace process,' said Mrs Hanan
Ashrawi, a Palestinian leader. 'Expecting Palestinians to live next to
settlers who are illegally occupying their land is like putting a flame next
to dynamite.'
Religious and secular Palestinian factions opposed to the peace process have
vowed to continue their struggle against Israel until, as a minimum, the
Jewish state withdraws behind the 'Green Line' - the disputed border before
the 1967 Arab-Israeli war.
Hamas, a disciplined and well organised underground movement responsible for
the most devastating recent attacks, wants to go further and wage a
religious war against the Jews until all of the land of Palestine is
liberated under Islamic rule.
'Violence will continue so long as occupation and stealing of Palestinian
land remains,' said Dr Omar Farwana, a Gaza City Hamas sympathiser.
'Resistance and struggle will go on until the last day of the liberation of
Palestine. Anybody saying something else is lying. All Palestinians feel the
coming days will see more intense and violent struggle against the settlers
and the soldiers because we think the main reason why Israeli soldiers left
Gaza was our resistance.'
The ability of Palestinian extremists to continue violent attacks against
Israel will depend on how the incoming Palestinian security forces deal with
the extremists. The PLO have said they intend to disarm the factions and
confiscate up to 20,000 weapons in Gaza alone.
Yesterday the ten factions opposed to the peace accord warned such a move
might provoke an internal Palestinian civil war. 'If the Palestinian police
try to disarm our people they will be subjecting themselves to grave
dangers,' said Mr Abu Mohammed Mustafa, a Hamas spokesman in Damascus. 'Our
men. . . will kill anyone who tries to deprive us of the right to confront
the enemy.'
Israel hopes that trust may grow between Arab and Jew during an interim
period of Palestinian self-rule. But Palestinians say until Arab grievances
such as settlements and Jerusalem are resolved the Middle East will remain a
region of violence.
</TEXT>
