<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / US warning to North Korea: Military readiness may be
increased, says Perry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr William Perry, US defence secretary, warned yesterday the US would
increase the already high 'readiness level' of its troops in South Korea if
it proved necessary to seek sanctions against North Korea.
This would be required, he told a group of foreign correspondents, because
of North Korean statements that sanctions would be equivalent to an 'act of
war'. He conceded that Pyongyang's assertions might be 'just rhetoric' and
he added that US forces would not be placed on 'a war footing,' but that
prudence dictated the US be ready for any eventuality.
Mr Perry emphasised that sanctions would not be sought if the International
Atomic Energy Inspection team now in North Korea reported back to the UN
that its safeguards against the diversion of nuclear material for military
purposes were being observed.
He said he had some 'hope but not optimism,' that a confrontation with North
Korea could be averted. He also refused to rule out the possibility that
China could support sanctions if it concluded that the US and its partners
had shown sufficient 'patience' in their dealings with Pyongyang.
'I believe the Chinese will make their decisions on sanctions based on where
their national interests lie,' he said. China did vote in favour of
tightened UN sanctions against Haiti earlier this month, but with the clear
caveat that that should not be interpreted as a precedent.
</TEXT>
