<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / World Trade News: US optimistic over Japan trade talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A senior US official yesterday said the US is 'in a listening mode' and
optimistic about the exploratory trade talks due to begin today in
Washington with a Japanese negotiating team, writes Nancy Dunne in
Washington.
'Obviously you don't send your officials all this way if there is not
something to be said,' the US official said. While not knowing what to
expect from the Japanese, the US negotiators expect to build on progress
achieved in bilateral talks in Marakesh when the Uruguay Round was signed.
Mr Mickey Kantor, the US trade representative, and Vice President Al Gore
then met at length with Mr Tsutomu Hata, Japan's new prime minister. The
senior US official said progress was made on macroeconomic issues and US
demands for objective indicators' to measure progress in sectoral market
openings.
However, there was stalemate on the US demand to set goals in the sectors
for which the Japanese promise to improve access.
Despite the failure in the overall 'framework talks,' Japan has succumbed to
US demands in a number of sectors this year, including apples, cellular
telephones, chemicals, and copper. 'We've had more agreements with the
Japanese this year than in any year in our history,' the senior official
said.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
    JPZ  Japan, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
