<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / World Trade News: Call to separate rights and China MFN
decision
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Support is growing in Congress for a strategy to separate the annual renewal
of China's Most Favoured Nation trade status from demands that it improve
its human rights policies.
A letter has been sent to President Bill Clinton from 106 members of both
parties which called for creation of a US-Chinese human rights commission as
a 'constructive and effective alternative' to the yearly confrontation over
MFN renewal. The commission could include government and private sector
experts on human rights, jurists, and business and religious leaders.
Meanwhile, State Department officials yesterday seemed to confirm reports
that Mr Clinton had sent a secret envoy to Beijing to urge progress on human
rights so that the president could renew China's MFN status. Mr Mike
McCurry, the State Department spokesman, did not deny the reports and
affirmed that there were 'many aspects of quiet diplomacy that we have been
pursuing.'
On June 3, the president must determine whether China has met the human
rights and immigration conditions linked to the renewal. Business lobbyists
have also urged the separation of MFN and human rights, warning that loss of
MFN would be almost as blighting to the US economy as China's.
On Sunday Senator George Mitchell, Senate majority leader, said he was
drafting trade sanctions, to be introduced in the Senate, in the event that
China fails to meet the conditions.
The Administration has been arguing that progress has been achieved in human
rights. However, continued detention of dissidents and only marginal
advances in China's treatment of Tibetans has undermined those claims.
</TEXT>
