<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / World Trade News: Commission censured over car agreement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER and JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The European Court yesterday censured the European Commission for failing to
investigate a long-standing Anglo-Japanese market-sharing agreement covering
Japanese car imports into the UK.
The Luxembourg-based Court of First Instance said the Commission had made a
'manifest error' of judgment in March 1992 when it declined to investigate
the 17-year-old pact.
The deal, between the Japanese Automobile Manufacturers' Association and the
UK's Society of Motor Manufacturers and Traders, was known as a 'gentlemen's
agreement'. It formally required only that the Japanese market its cars
'prudently' in the UK. Effectively, however, it limited the market share for
Japanese cars to 11 per cent.
The Court's intervention - which followed a complaint by BEUC, the European
consumer bureau, and the UK-based National Consumer Council - last night
appeared to throw the SMMT into confusion because the 'gentlemen's
agreement' was formally ended in 1992.
This followed completion of an agreement between the EU Commission and
Japan's Ministry of Trade and Industry. This devised a formula for
controlling Japanese car imports on a Europe-wide basis during a transition
to a completely open EU market for cars by 1999 where informal import
ceilings for each country are reviewed twice a year.
Under the EU-Miti accord, all previous national restrictions on Japanese car
imports became illegal. Both France and Italy had much tighter restrictions
than the UK.
The SMMT said it was taking legal advice about the ruling but 'we don't
understand what the court is talking about. The agreement finished in 1992
and the Commission was duly informed of that'.
The Commission said yesterday it was digesting the implications of the
ruling.
BEUC brought the case on the grounds that the arrangement between the
British and Japanese manufacturers associations made prices higher and
infringed EU competition law.
The Commission argued that the pact affected only a small proportion of
trade between EU member states.
</TEXT>
