<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / World Trade News: NCM may expand into Asia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RONALD VAN DE KROL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   AMSTERDAM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NCM, the Dutch-based international credit insurer, said yesterday it was
considering expanding into Asia, where credit insurance was relatively
under-developed compared with Europe, the group's main market, writes Ronald
van de Krol in Amsterdam.
Mr Harry Groen, NCM's chairman, said the company hoped to have a 'presence
of one form or another' in Asia within the next couple of years, extending
growth abroad that has seen the company buy or launch operations in six
countries, including Britain, since the early 1990s.
NCM last year insured deliveries of goods and services worth Fl 147.9bn
(Pounds 52.6bn). Recent economic difficulties in Germany had led to a rise
in credit insurance claims from companies doing business with German
customers.
The company had also recently tightened its policy on covering trade credits
on business with Italy, Spain and Portugal because of several years of high
claims.
