<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / World Trade News: Chile-EU fruit tariffs lowered
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID PILLING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SANTIAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Chile has won agreement for lower tariffs on its apples and pears exported
to the European Union, David Pilling writes from Santiago.
In return Chile has dropped its request that Gatt investigate EU
restrictions on its fruit.
Chilean fruit producers, who account for 12 per cent of EU consumption, say
the European system of countervailing duties last year caused them losses of
Dollars 100m-Dollars 120m (Pounds 66.6m - Pounds 80m).
Tariffs will be lowered by 50 per cent under the agreement reached in
Brussels on Tuesday. The reference price - the level at which import
surcharges come into effect - will also be raised. Chile will be allowed to
export 12 per cent of fruit below this price, against 8 per cent previously.
</TEXT>
