<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / GAO rings alarm bells over danger of derivatives
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The fragmented US regulatory structure is badly organised to deal with the
fast-growing derivatives markets. The result: the markets have come to be
dominated by several big dealers, some of which are completely unregulated.
The failure of any one of these could bring the US - and, by extension, the
world's - financial system to its knees.
Those are the conclusions of the General Accounting Office, Congress's
investigating arm, in its long-awaited report on derivatives published
yesterday. Its warnings are the most apocalyptic yet to emanate from the
string of official reports carried out in the US and elsewhere in the past
two years into the derivatives markets.
The GAO concludes: 'The immediate need is for Congress to bring the
currently unregulated OTC (over-the-counter) derivatives activities of
securities firms and insurance company affiliates under the purview of one
or more of the existing federal financial regulators and to ensure that
derivatives regulation is consistent and comprehensive across regulatory
agencies.'
The markets are concentrated in very few hands, says the report: just seven
US banks accounted for 90 per cent of derivatives activity in the US at the
end of 1992. These entities also dominate a large part of global trading
activity. 'This combination of global involvement, concentration, and
linkages means that sudden failure or abrupt withdrawal from trading of any
of these large dealers could cause liquidity problems in the markets and
could also pose risks to the others, including federally insured banks and
the financial system as a whole.'
The agency's main proposal is for legislation to bring the unregulated
derivative trading units of securities houses and insurance companies into
the regulatory net. At end 1992, these companies already accounted for 30
per cent of over-the-counter activity in the US (the rest was carried out by
banks.)
'Congress (should) require federal regulation of the safety and soundness of
all main US over-the-counter derivatives dealers,' it says. Either the
Securities and Exchange Commission should be responsible for the unregulated
dealers, with a new inter-agency group set up to establish common regulatory
standards; or leadership in setting regulations for derivatives should be
divided between different regulatory bodies, depending on their particular
expertise.
The report also calls for the urgent modernisation of the entire financial
regulatory system in the US. 'The existing regulatory structure has not kept
pace with the dramatic and rapid changes in the domestic and global
financial markets' of recent years, it says. It does not offer solutions to
this perceived problem, but it says: 'Many issues need to be debated and
decided, including the appropriate uses of federally insured deposits and
the extent to which they should be used to finance large-scale proprietary
trading in derivatives or other financial instruments.'
Financial regulators, meanwhile, should work together to make combined
efforts more effective, the GAO says. This could be done by centralising
information about firms they regulate, operating a consistent set of rules
governing the capital which dealers are required to hold, and requiring
dealers to have independent audit committees and adequate internal controls
for their derivatives activities. It also calls for annual full-scale
examinations of all dealers once a year.
A second focus of regulatory attention should be the accounting and
disclosure regime for derivatives, the GAO says. It calls for rules
requiring both dealers and users of derivatives to publish more about their
activities in this area, and a consistent accounting regime that can be
applied to all types of instrument.
Finally, the report calls for the SEC to extend derivatives regulation to
many publicly-traded companies which use such instruments.
'SEC registrants that are major end-users of complex derivative products
(should) establish and implement corporate requirements for independent,
knowledgeable audit committees and public reporting on internal controls.'
External auditors should also be required to report on the quality of
risk-management systems for derivatives, it adds.
Financial Derivatives - Actions Needed to Protect the Financial System, GAO
documents office, telephone Washington 512 6000. First copy free, additional
copies Dollars 2.
</TEXT>
<XX>
