<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Rough ride for bill on healthcare reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US legislators are facing an uphill task as they begin the thorny task of
drawing up a health reform bill. Despite a willingness to make concessions
from a few closely involved in the process, a consensus remains as far away
as ever.
Two of the five congressional committees overseeing the overhaul of the US
healthcare system started the formal process of drawing up a bill yesterday.
In the Senate labor and human resources committee, Republicans yesterday set
out to attack from all sides a proposal from Senator Edward Kennedy of
Massachusetts, the committee's chairman, which preserves many aspects of
President Bill Clinton's plan while limiting the requirements that would be
placed on small businesses.
But Mr Kennedy's proposal is expected to win support from almost all of his
committee's 10 Democratic members, enough to overrule the seven-member
Republican minority.
In the House of Representatives, Congressman Dan Rostenkowski is not so sure
of the backing of all the Democrats on his ways and means committee, which
also began a drafting session yesterday.
Mr Rostenkowski has warned his members that they must face the uncomfortable
choices posed by the reform of health care. The reform raises the prospect
of a general tax increase to pay for it if members are unwilling to adopt
the employer mandate contained in Mr Clinton's plan, under which employers
would have to pay 80 per cent of the costs of health insurance for their
workers.
The employer mandate has appeared in recent weeks to be sticking in
Congress's throat, with Republicans and many centrist Democrats objecting
that it would cost jobs by raising costs for businesses.
But signals of a possible compromise are emerging, with some senior
legislators now willing to accept some form of mandate, so long as smaller
businesses are exempted.
Senator John Breaux of Louisiana has come up with a proposal that would
require large companies to provide health insurance for their workforce but
exempt employers with 10 or fewer workers and levying a payroll tax on those
with between 11 and 20 workers.
Mr Breaux represents a vital swing vote on the Senate finance committee,
where Democrats outnumber Republicans by only 11 to nine. The finance
committee has so far made less progress than any of the other principal
committees towards drafting a bill.
</TEXT>
