<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Protest by Balaguer opponent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CANUTE JAMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KINGSTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Jose Francisco Pena Gomez, a candidate for the presidency of the
Dominican Republic, has asked the electoral board to stop publishing the
results of the count, and not to declare the results of Monday's election
until it investigates his party's allegations of fraud and corruption in the
voting.
Mr Pena Gomez, who is trying to become the country's first black president,
made the request as returns from the election showed his social democrat
Dominican Revolutionary Party to be running a close second to the
conservative Social Christian Reform Party led by Mr Joaquin Balaguer, the
president. Mr Balaguer, at 87, is seeking a seventh term.
With 81 per cent of the votes counted yesterday, Mr Balaguer had 42.76 per
cent, with Mr Pena Gomez on 40.95 per cent. Mr Pena Gomez has claimed that
up to 200,000 people, most of them his supporters, were unable to vote
either because their voting cards had been confiscated, or their names were
not on the list.
</TEXT>
