<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Karel Van Miert, EU competition commissioner, yesterday threw his weight
publicly behind a full and speedy liberalisation of Europe's cable
television infrastructure. The commissioner, outlining the role of
competition policy in telecommunications, said his aides were studying the
impact of allowing cable TV companies to offer services already open to
competition, such as alarm services and data bases. This would not include
voice telephony to the public. 'The central issue we have to address is
whether such an initiative would undermine the ability of the incumbent
telecoms operator to provide universal service. It is my conviction that
this is not the case,' said Mr Van Miert.
