<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Nato rebuff for Russians
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE CLARK
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Nato ambassadors yesterday rebuffed Moscow's demand for an alternative to
the Partnership for Peace arrangement, in a move that casts a shadow over
next week's visit to Brussels by General Pavel Grachev, the Russian defence
minister. Gen Grachev has said Russia is not prepared simply to join the
queue of East European countries signing up to the partnership, an
arrangement that provides for joint exercises and an exchange of military
know-how. At a meeting in Brussels yesterday, the ambassadors said the most
they could promise was 'dialogue and co-operation' of a kind that reflected
Russia's importance in European security.
However, this dialogue would be in addition to Russian adherence to the
partnership, not a substitute. An alliance spokesman said Nato 'looked
forward' to Russia subscribing to the partnership, which already has 18
members. 'We do not like the term special relationship,' said a Nato
official, adding that any links between Russia and the alliance must be
transparent and stop well short of giving Moscow a veto over future alliance
decisions.
