<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Berlusconi wins senate backing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Silvio Berlusconi, Italy's new prime minister, last night cleared the
last hurdle to begin governing with his right-wing cabinet when he narrowly
won a vote of confidence in the senate.
Mr Berlusconi's Freedom Alliance lacked an absolute majority in the 315-seat
senate, swelled to 326 by 11 life senators. He had to rely on the absence of
some senators and the abstention of others to win the vote by 159 to 153,
with two abstentions.
The abstentions counted as a negative; but those absent either through ill
health, travel or tactical reasons simply reduced the size of the majority
required. With an absolute majority in the chamber of deputies, the
confidence vote there on Friday is a foregone conclusion. Mr Berlusconi can
now begin to flesh out the details of deregulating the economy, ending
Italy's rigid labour laws and reforming taxes, which he announced earlier
this week would be the centrepiece of his first 100 days.
The three-day debate in the senate showed many politicians were concerned
about the composition of the new government, with its five ministers drawn
from the neo-fascist MSDI/National Alliance and the presence of the populist
Northern League. But despite such reservations no one suggested a serious
alternative to Mr Berlusconi or his chosen allies.
</TEXT>
