FT  19 MAY 94 / Cod quota cuts hit Iceland
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   Stockholm
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Iceland is facing another difficult year in 1994 due to sharp cuts in cod
quotas and can expect only a modest recovery next year, according to the
Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development. An OECD report says
the economy will decline by 1.2 per cent this year, after growing by a
better-than-expected 0.8 per cent last year. The report says Iceland's
fishing industry, which accounts for 75 per cent of exports, is going
through a difficult phase because of past overfishing and unfavourable
environmental conditions. The total allowable cod catch has been cut by 20
per cent in the year to September 1994. The organisation says fisheries
management is Iceland's key policy challenge but believes further reform of
agriculture is also required. Payments to the sector should be gradually
reduced.
