<PROFILE>_AN-EESCVAASFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940519
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Journalist in a class of his own: Obituary of Robert
Mauthner
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Robert Mauthner, who died yesterday at the age of 65, would be proud to be
remembered simply as a journalist. But journalists are ten a penny. What
marked him out - as a foreign correspondent, diplomatic editor and deputy
foreign editor for the Financial Times in a career spanning 25 years, and
before that for Reuters - was that he belonged in that rare class of its
own: he was the most professional of journalists.
His countless colleagues, friends, peers and contacts all knew that he would
get it right and write it properly. His stamina was legendary, his fairness
and accuracy without equal, his knowledge and experience invaluable. From
Prague to Paris, from Helsinki to Kuala Lumpur, he always delivered the
goods meticulously, as a reporter, analyst and columnist.
Those who worked with him also loved many other qualities. He was an
incomparable counsellor and mentor, a role model who always gave his advice
and time unstintingly to those below and above him. He was often the first
into the office and invariably among the last to leave. Stories, he would
say, could not be left to chance. He grieved more than most over mistakes or
misinterpretations which he thought the newspaper should have avoided, but
he would be as pleased as punch, and generous in his praise, whenever we
beat the competition.
And he knew when this had happened; he read every newspaper he could lay his
hands on with a fine eye - in English, French, German, Dutch and probably a
few other languages besides.
He came to the FT almost casually. In 1968, having left Reuters in Brussels,
he was asked to fill in for our vacationing Bonn correspondent. When
Dubcek's Prague spring flowered and with FT foreign correspondents then much
thinner on the ground, he was sent to Czechoslovakia, from which he reported
with such distinction that when he finally left after the Soviet tanks had
rolled in he was immediately recruited to the foreign staff.
Three years later, he was chief correspondent in Paris, a post he held for
more than 10 years. His affection for and knowledge of France was
deep-rooted, but that never affected his detachment. He infused a succession
of younger, junior correspondents in the bureau with his standards, to the
point that all acknowledge their debt to him.
After a stint running the London foreign desk, he picked up the diplomatic
beat that was always close to his heart. But he was never content to confine
this to coverage of the British foreign office, though he never neglected
it. A European by conviction long before it was fashionable, he covered the
interstices of the Community's and Nato's security affairs and the
implications of the tearing down of the Berlin Wall.
Summits were always grist to his mill, whether of the European,
Commonwealth, G7, Nato or CSCE variety. At Maastricht in 1991, when so much
was happening and when the FT had a large team of experts deployed, there
was no other choice but Bob for the unenviable task of pulling it all
together into a coherent front page story.
Yet, as the map of Europe was changing, he also pulled more than the
required weight as deputy foreign editor in London. His advice on whom to
move where and when was always wise, as was his judgment of what was
important. Successive foreign editors knew they could always leave their
charge in his hands.
He could be crusty and obstinate. But the more cantankerous he became the
more it was apparent that he was standing on principle. If that made others
uncomfortable it was a price worth paying for fighting for what he knew to
be right.
All the above made him exceptionally respected as the professional
journalist, the heart, soul and mind of so much of our foreign coverage for
a generation. But the sheer sense of loss now consuming his friends and
colleagues attests to a much deeper affection extending well outside the
newsroom.
He was great company, preferably over a good meal and bottle, but also over
a bad pub sandwich and a pint. He loved his sports and if rugby was his
sneaking favourite, his tastes were catholic. He made us laugh, sometimes
with a wonderful line in what might be called poetic doggerel-plus. Even
though we all knew he would never really lay down his pen, there was a new
flat waiting for him in Paris with his wife Anne for his notional
retirement. No spare room would ever have been more permanently booked.
                          *      *      *
 ----------------------------------------------------------------
                  ROBERT MAUTHNER 1929-1994
 ----------------------------------------------------------------
1929 Born in Amsterdam
1939 School in Isle of Wight
1949-52 Wadham College, Oxford
1952 Became British citizen
1952-54 Military service
1954-56 Early journalistic career Wakefield Express
1956-57 Reuters, London
1957-61 English language service, French radio, Paris
1961 Reuters bureau chief in Brussels
1967 Caused flurry in House of Commons with scoop on UK
     entry into EEC
1968 FT European correspondent
1971 Paris correspondent
1981 Deputy foreign editor and foreign news editor
1983 Diplomatic correspondent
1992-94 Diplomatic editor
 ----------------------------------------------------------------
