<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / The tributes
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Douglas Hurd, UK foreign secretary, paid the following personal tribute
to Bob Mauthner yesterday:
'I was sad to hear of Bob Mauthner's death.  He gave shape to that
ill-defined role of Diplomatic Editor, I was always impressed by his grasp
of foreign policy and his ability to explain the issues clearly and
objectively.
Good journalism, produced with real knowledge and authority, helps people -
policy makers as well as voters - understand and assess problems better.
Bob was a highly distinguished journalist, and we shall miss him.'
Hella Pick, president, Diplomatic and Commonwealth Writers' Association,
associate foreign editor, The Guardian:
'I feel a very deep loss.  He was a loyal friend and good companion. I
always envied his writing - I never knew anyone who could put so much into
his first paragraphs that made so much sense.'
Mr Stephen Somerville, director, Reuter Foundation:
'Reuters remembers Bob as one of the best-informed and most perceptive
observers of the European scene, including during the 1960s when he achieved
several notable scoops on political developments like Britain's efforts to
join the Common Market.'
</TEXT>
