<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / The real contest to succeed Delors now begins: With
Sutherland in, the opaque process of electing a Commission president is made
more public
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Over the next month, European Union leaders will be sounded out by the
current Greek presidency of the Twelve on who they want to succeed Mr
Jacques Delors at the head of the European Commission.
If, as still expected, there is a loud enough murmur in favour of outgoing
Dutch premier Ruud Lubbers, this opaque selection process could be over in
minutes when the 12 heads of government convene at the Corfu summit on June
24-25.
But if a contest develops between Mr Lubbers and his fellow Christian
Democrat, Mr Jean-Luc Dehaene, the prime minister of Belgium, then Mr Peter
Sutherland, the Irish director general of the General Agreement on Tariffs
and Trade, who threw his hat in the ring on Tuesday night, is in with a
chance.
Mr Sutherland, a consumate self-publicist with a nice sense of timing,
clearly thinks so. He concedes that the question is 'entirely hypothetical',
but that if asked to put himself forward, 'I would have to give it serious
consideration'. But will he be asked?
The Commission presidency race is about as permeable to outsiders as a papal
succession. EU governments leak or intimate what they say are their
preferences as the process evolves, but with the tactics and knowledge that
all 12 'cardinals' have in the end to be unanimous.
Sir Leon Brittan, the external economic affairs commissioner, has very
openly campaigned for Mr Delors' job. This has done European citizens the
service of generating what little public debate there is about who should
fill it, although it is unlikely to be him, simply because he is from
Britain, a semi-detached member state with two opt-outs from the Maastricht
treaty.
Mr Sutherland's publicly discreet declaration has enlivened the game, and
should now generate more debate.
Like Sir Leon in 1989-92, he was a forceful competition commissioner in
Brussels in 1985-88. His Euro-credentials are sound, he is ambitious, and
after securing the Uruguay Round world trade deal he is a figure on the
international stage.
After the 10-year tenure of Mr Delors, a French Socialist, EU club rules
point to a conservative from a small member state. Mr Lubbers, a cautious
Euro-Atlanticist, and Mr Dehaene, a mainstream federalist, are both
Christian Democrats from small countries who fit the bill. As an Irish
liberal, so too does Mr Sutherland.
But his only chance is if they both stay in the race, enabling him to come
up the middle as a compromise candidate.
This is still a long shot. First, the Sutherland challenge will force Mr
Lubbers to campaign, according to the word from the Hague. The Dutchman has
already been in Athens, and can be expected in other main capitals soon.
Second, the Christian Democrats are not the inner-EU club they once were.
After Mr Lubbers' own defeat in the Netherlands, they are down to the
coalitions they command in Luxembourg, Belgium, and Germany.
An intra-Christian Democrat fight under these circumstances is unlikely, and
Mr Dehaene is understood not to want to take on Mr Lubbers publicly.
Only Spain has sounded Mr Sutherland out, although he could almost certainly
count on Britain's support. But Chancellor Helmut Kohl, who has no personal
warmth for Mr Lubbers, is still likely to want to get a Christian Democrat
in, and to do a deal with France, which despite its close relations with
Ireland, is more likely to favour Mr Dehaene.
Mr Sutherland has a big domestic problem to overcome as well. He is a member
of the opposition Fine Gael party in Ireland, at a time when Fianna Fail and
the Labour party govern in coalition. The current Irish commissioner for
social affairs, Mr Padraig Flynn from Fianna Fail, has made it clear he has
no intention of making way for Mr Sutherland.
Mr Albert Reynolds, the Irish prime minister, would therefore have to be
assured by his colleagues that Ireland was getting the Commission presidency
before contemplating switching horses. Yesterday in parliament, Mr Reynolds
said his own election agent was about as likely to get the job.
But the Dublin government has come under sufficient pressure from questions
in the Dail and speculation in the Irish press for Mr Dick Spring, the
foreign minister and deputy prime minister, to say in Brussels this week
that if Mr Sutherland wanted the job, he should indicate his interest.
This the Gatt chief has now done, and neither component of the Irish
coalition would relish being charged with passing up the chance of what Mr
Sutherland heavily underlined as 'a very important position for Ireland, for
Europe, and the world.' The real contest now begins.
</TEXT>
<XX>
