<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAY 94 / Tighter control of derivatives urged: Report to Congress
warns of threat to financial system
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS and PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Inadequate regulation of the rapidly growing markets in derivatives,
financial instruments such as swaps and options, poses a threat to the US
and international financial system, according to a landmark report to
Congress published yesterday.
The report, by the General Accounting Office, recommends legislation to
extend regulation to all financial firms which deal in derivatives, as well
as a consistent approach to regulation from the various financial
authorities in the US.
In an unusual show of solidarity, a coalition of trade groups representing
the banking and securities industries issued a joint statement condemning
the call for tighter regulation.
The report will increase the pressure for US legislation to control
derivatives markets. Commissioned two years ago, it concludes that much of
the activity in over-the-counter markets in instruments such as interest
rate swaps and currency options is unregulated and concentrated among a few
big institutions.
The agency, which acts as Congress's investigative arm, warns that the
failure or withdrawal of any one of these institutions 'could undermine
stability in several markets simultaneously, which could lead to a chain of
market withdrawals, possible firm failures, and a systemic crisis'.
Mr Edward Markey, chairman of the key House Telecommunications and Finance
sub-committee, which is responsible for drafting legislation covering the
securities industry, indicated for the first time that he will push for
legislation.
'The question is no longer whether regulatory or legislative changes will be
made affecting the derivatives markets, but what form such changes should
take,' he said.
Staff members of the House Banking Committee, which already has its own bill
in preparation, indicated that the report would improve the chances of
legislation being passed.
Lawmakers will have the first opportunity to air their concerns today, as Mr
Markey's committee and the senate banking committee will hold hearings on
the subject. Mr Charles Bowsher, comptroller general and head of the GAO,
will appear before both to answer questions on the report.
However, early legislation in the area is unlikely, a staff member of Mr
Markey's committee indicated. He said a bill will probably not be ready
before the July recess. The House banking committee expects to publish a
final version of its own bill early next month.
Any legislation is likely to be opposed by the derivatives industry.
Yesterday, the Securities Industry Association, the American Bankers
Association, the International Swap and Derivatives Association and three
other financial services trade groups warned that further regulation would
harm the US economy by increasing the cost and reducing the availability of
derivative transactions. They criticised the GAO study for being out of date
and for failing to take into account changes that derivatives dealers and
users have made in recent years to improve disclosure, internal controls and
risk management techniques.
Derivatives, said the trade groups, 'are an essential component of modern
financial activity'. Rather than heightening risk in the financial system,
the trade groups said derivatives make it possible to quantify and manage
risks more effectively than ever before.
GAO sounds alarm, Page 4
Editorial Comment, Page 23
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
