<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 94 / London Stock Exchange: Hanson payment pleases
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON, CHRISTOPHER PRICE and JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Turnover in Anglo-US conglomerate Hanson jumped to 24m shares, making it the
day's most actively traded FT-SE 100 constituent, after it surprised the
market with an increase in the dividend. The stock gained 6 at 269p.
The hefty volume included a single block of 6.9m traded at 259p, thought to
have been part of a tax-related deal.
News on the dividend accompanied interim figures which revealed headline
profits of Pounds 683m - against Pounds 507m a year earlier - a figure which
disappointed several analysts. The dividend was raised from 2.85p to 3p.
Mr Geoff Allum at NatWest Securities was among those disappointed by the
profits figure but conceded: 'As a yield stock the increase in the dividend
overshadows the less than expected profits.'
