<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 94 / International Company News: USAir forced to delay delivery
of new aircraft
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
USAir, the US airline in which British Airways holds a minority stake, has
postponed delivery of 40 Boeing 737 jetliners and cancelled options for
another 76 Boeing aircraft, it emerged yesterday.
Separately, a ballot among the airline's 8,000 fleet service workers
indicated they were set to join a labour union in an attempt to win better
protection against the shake-out in the US airline industry.
USAir, which faces acute pressure to cut costs because of competition from
low-cost airlines making inroads into its east coast market, had planned to
take delivery of the 40 737 jets between 1997 and 2000.
A filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission shows it has deferred
delivery of the airliners to dates between 2003 and 2005. It has also
cancelled options for 63 737s, 11 757s and two 767s, but it will still take
delivery of 18 757s between now and 1996.
</TEXT>
