<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 94 / Braer report calls for urgent action on shipping: Inquiry
finds significant incidence of human error
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A call for urgent action to cut the chance of human error in shipping and
reduce the danger of pollution of the seas was made in an official report
published yesterday.
Lord Donaldson's inquiry into the prevention of shipping pollution, launched
after the sinking of the oil tanker Braer, has made more than 100
recommendations for improved safety procedures.
The Braer, a Liberian-registered tanker, spilled 85,000 tonnes of Norwegian
oil into the sea off Shetland in January 1993 after sea water entered its
diesel tanks and caused engine failure.
Responding to the report, Safer Ships, Cleaner Seas, Mr John MacGregor,
transport secretary, announced plans to shame shipowners into raising
standards by publishing a monthly list of sub-standard ships calling at UK
ports, detailing the names of vessels, their defects, flags and owners.
Lord Donaldson and his inquiry team said they 'were surprised and alarmed at
the number of potentially serious incidents which took place during the
course of the inquiry . . . Although none resulted in major pollution, it
was largely a matter of chance that they did not'.
The report identified human failings as the cause of virtually all
accidental pollution from ships, and said the best preventative measure was
improved maintenance and operation standards.
Its recommendations include:
A tougher system for inspecting ships arriving in port. An increase in the
number of tugs around the UK coastline. Improved sharing of information
between charterers, insurers, shipping agents and regulatory bodies on the
standards of ships and fleets. Substandard ships would then have difficulty
finding cargoes and increase their insurance premiums.
Better identification of ships at sea by painting their international radio
call sign on their sides and decks. The creation of Marine Environmental
High Risk Areas, a small number of areas which are both environmentally
sensitive and on busy shipping routes.
The inquiry said these measures would cost about Pounds 10m with the bill to
be shared by the government and shipowners.
Mr Frank Dobson, Labour transport spokesman, called for the North Sea states
to bring in tough new regulations to enforce better standards because of the
failure of the 'flag states' to act. Numast, the ships' officers union, said
it was concerned that planned cutbacks at the department of transport's
marine safety agency would undermine the inquiry's recommendations.
Broad welcome for report, Page 7
Editorial Comment, Page 21
</TEXT>
