<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 94 / Sutherland ready to join race for EU presidency
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The race to succeed Mr Jacques Delors as president of the European
Commission was joined last night by Mr Peter Sutherland, the Irish
director-general of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (Gatt), who
signalled he was available for the job.
Mr Sutherland, whose leadership at Gatt was instrumental in securing the
Uruguay Round world trade liberalisation deal, recently said he would be
stepping down at the end of the year.
'If I was asked the question about being a candidate (for the Commission
presidency) by a member state then I would have to give it serious
consideration,' Mr Sutherland said.
He told RTE, Irish television, that 'it's an entirely hypothetical
situation'. But he stressed twice that 'it's a very important position for
Ireland, for Europe and the world'.
Mr Sutherland's candidacy opens up a field which includes Mr Ruud Lubbers,
the outgoing Dutch prime minister, Mr Jean-Luc Dehaene, the Belgian premier,
and Sir Leon Brittan, the senior British commissioner in charge of the EU's
external economic relations.
The Irishman, a successful competition commissioner in Brussels in 1984-88,
is a plausible if long-shot compromise. But he must pick up endorsements
from leading member states - particularly Germany - and win the support of
Dublin. The EU's 12 heads of government are expected to decide on Mr Delors'
successor at their summit in Corfu on June 24-25.
It is understood that of the larger member states, only Spain has so far
sounded out Mr Sutherland. The Gatt chief has a Spanish wife, and a
Commission president from Ireland, which is a member of the 'Cohesion' group
of the four poorest member states including Spain, Portugal and Greece,
would be a useful ally for Madrid.
Mr Lubbers remains the front-runner, but has less than warm relations with
Chancellor Helmut Kohl. Mr Kohl is said by some leading EU officials to
favour Mr Dehaene, who could also get backing from Paris. Sir Leon is
hampered by being from the UK, which has opt-outs from the Maastricht
treaty.
CBI chief vents wrath on Brussels, Page 8
