<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 94 / Observer: Out of the bag
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Who was the journalist who has admitted making up previous accounts of
clashes between the Bank of England and the Treasury?
Kenneth Clarke, the 'business friendly' Chancellor of the Exchequer, dropped
the tantalising reference into his CBI speech last night in a bid to prove
that the publication of the regular monetary chats between the Treasury and
the Bank of England led to a better informed debate.
The Chancellor likened his actions to introducing 'Red Indians to whisky' -
it was heady stuff for journalists, he said.
But who was the journalist who let the side down? Surely not Rupert
Pennant-Rea, ex-editor of the Economist and now deputy governor of the Bank
of England. All Clarke's officials would say was that it was a 'state
secret'.
</TEXT>
