<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
You have to hand it to television drama departments: though they know
viewers would rather be entertained, they stick doggedly to serious social
issues. Today's 'Screen Two' is Sin Bin in which Pete Postlethwaite plays a
nurse in a mental hospital who sees a colleague batter one of the patients
to death. Should he blow the whistle or turn a blind eye? (9.00 BBC2). It
will be surprising if the audience for that is anything like as big as the
audience for Three Men And A Baby on ITV, even though the 1987 movie has
been shown on television before. Ted Danson, Steve Guttenberg, and Tom
Selleck star as three bachelors who prove to be incompetent when they are
landed with a baby girl to look after (8.00). Inside Story looks at the real
life 'manageress' of the football world: Karren Brady, managing director of
Birmingham City FC. We are assured that she was appointed not because club
owner David Sullivan, who made a fortune from girlie magazines, thought it a
good gimmick to choose a photogenic 23-year-old blonde, but because she was
the right person for the job (9.40 BBC1).
