<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 94 / Subsidies on mobiles rapped
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Don Cruickshank, the telecommunications regulator, ruled yesterday that
mobile phone operators were 'un-fairly' cross-subsidising service providers
owned by them.
He said he would oblige the operators to pay a reasonable return to service
providers for connecting mobile phone users, in a ruling likely to favour
the remaining independent service providers. There are about 20 service
providers.
The ruling follows complaints by service providers not owned by one of the
four cellular network operators - Vodafone, Cellnet, Mercury One-2-One and
Orange - that the low margins paid to them were making their business
uneconomic.
Nearly half the network subscribers of Vodafone and Cellnet are connected
via providers partly or wholly owned by them. Mr Cruickshank said he was
'determined this market should operate in a completely fair and open
manner'.
The complaints were launched in 1992 by Talkland, then an independent
provider. Vodafone, the largest network operator has since bought a
one-third stake in the company.
Mr Charles Wigoder, managing director of the independent Peoples Phone,
said: 'This is good news for the independent service providers, but it does
not change the fact that the economies of scale in the industry casts doubt
on the future of the smaller independents.'
Practice throughout the industry is to subsidise the acquisition of
subscribers. Mr Cruickshank ruled that 'mature' service providers should
make a reasonable return on this investment.
</TEXT>
