<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 94 / Insurers gloomy about prospects
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Encouraging customers to look ahead and consider the ills that could befall
them is a classic pitch for selling life insurance. The life industry itself
might be forgiven for being in sombre mood as it contemplates what lies
ahead.
Certainly some in the industry believe that the fall in new life and
pensions business revealed in the statistics from the Association of British
Insurers for the first three months of this year represents more than a
passing cloud.
The combination of tougher regulatory requirements and intensifying
competition looks like having an enduring and damping impact on the amount
of new business written in the months to come. The reluctance of some
leading companies to be drawn on the figures tells its own story.
Regulation seems to have acted as a depressant on new business in more than
one way.
On pensions business, the association highlighted the effect on
single-premium pension business of the uncertainty created by the
regulators' review of pension transfers launched in December after a pilot
study caused widespread concern about standards of selling.
That uncertainty has affected not only customers but also life insurers:
some of them are still not writing any pension transfer business and others
are being more cautious.
More generally, Mr Steve Maran, chief executive of Lloyds Abbey Life, is
among those to have highlighted the effort that needs to be put into meeting
new standards in training and the sales process as a diversion from current
selling.
Others suggest that the concentration on dealing with new regulatory
requirements may have detracted from designing new products to meet new
customer needs.
As Mr Tom King, general manager in charge of marketing at Standard Life, put
it: 'Product development has perhaps not kept pace with the changing
market.'
Association figures suggest that life companies have also been affected by
other forms of savings such as personal equity plans (Peps) and tax-exempt
special savings accounts (Tessas). The success of some National Savings
products, already identified as contributing to successive monthly outflows
from building societies' retail deposits, may be another factor.
One company commented: 'Investment performance hasn't been that great, so
perhaps customers did not think it worth the risk to go for life products
rather than National Savings.'
</TEXT>
