<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 94 / Make Ecu a business currency, says think-tank
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Ecu should be used as a parallel currency to allow business to deal in a
single tender across Europe, a new paper by a leading rightwing think-tank
argues today.
The paper, published by the Institute of Economic Affairs, which influenced
Baroness Thatcher during her term as prime minister, says that a parallel
Ecu is needed by business given that monetary union has receded to a distant
dream.
The paper's authors, who have expressed these opinions before, stress there
are now powerful economic reasons for a united, parallel currency. The
kaleidoscope of national currencies has been calculated to cost European
business Ecu15bn (Pounds 19.5bn), it says, with 55 per cent of companies
agreeing that savings from a single currency could exceed 1.5 per cent of
turnover.
Recent European Commission res-earch suggests that many businesses already
use the existing abstract Ecu measure in their transactions, with the Ecu
bond market the fifth largest in Europe.
A parallel currency need not entail any loss of political sovereignty, the
paper says.
The key to their scenario is a 'basket' Ecu, compiled from a weighted
average of community currencies.
This would require only minimal political agreement to introduce or manage,
they argue, saying that notes and coins could be issued by national banks or
even private currency boards, instead of the European Monetary Institute.
The Road to Monetary Union Revisited; by John Chown, Geoffrey E Wood and
Massimo Beber. The Institute of Economic Affairs, 2 Lord North Street,
London. SW1P 3lB. Pounds 3.50.
</TEXT>
