<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 94 / Price war is forecast for life policies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Commission disclosure in the life insurance industry will quickly trigger a
price war as banks and building societies take advantage of their lower
distribution costs, says accountancy firm Coopers &amp; Lybrand.
The ability to price products differentially to reflect the costs of selling
through various distribution channels will lead life companies which use
more than one channel to concentrate on their core method of distribution,
it forecasts.
Differential pricing is to be allowed in the new regime for disclosing more
information about commissions and costs. The regime, which requires the new
disclosure rules to be met by the start of next year, has been demanded by
regulators.
A Coopers analysis of the costs of companies operating mainly through one of
three distribution channels - banks, independent financial advisers and a
direct sales force - suggests that a significant price differential exists
for the banks and building societies.
The estimated average costs of acquiring new business as a percentage of
annual premium equivalent (regular premium income plus 10 per cent of single
premium income) range from 60 per cent for banks and building societies to
89 per cent for those using independent advisers and 95 per cent for
companies using a direct sales force.
Mr Angus Hislop, a senior financial services partner at Coopers, said
yesterday that the analysis also highlighted the scope for cost savings. In
each category, the highest expense ratio in the range was at least 25
percentage points higher than the average. Among companies using mainly
independent advisers it was more than 50 percentage points higher.
The Coopers forecast points in the same direction as research last month by
the Securities and Investments Board which suggested that commissions would
fall by about 20 per cent as a result of the new regime.
Mr Hislop said that he would expect the move to have the worst impact on
smaller, non-specialised sales forces. It would not affect independent
advisers so badly because there had already been a shake-out in that part of
the sector.
He added that, while distribution through banks and building societies was
clearly the cheapest method, the life-product proportion of overheads for
bank and building society branch networks should rise. That would happen as
more space in branches was devoted to selling and less to processing
transactions.
</TEXT>
