FT  18 MAY 94 / Cut-price sale for troubled project
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
South Quay, a large part-finished office building opposite Canary Wharf in
the London Docklands, is believed to have been sold to an overseas buyer for
about Pounds 7m, about a tenth of its original cost.
South Quay, 360,000 sq ft of space including an unfinished 17-storey tower
block, went into receivership in May 1992. The purchaser intends to hold the
development until market conditions improve.
The South Quay development consists of three separate office buildings above
two floors of shops.
Two buildings - comprising 144 self-contained business apartments and 30
retail units - are virtually complete while the third building, which
includes the tower block, is part-completed.
South Quay was built by Wiggins Group, a property developer, and established
as a separate company in 1990 when Wiggins underwent financial
restructuring.
