<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 94 / Brown's bandwagon starts to roll
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The complexities of Labour's leadership battle deepened yesterday as friends
of Mr Gordon Brown suggested that he might stand against Mr Tony Blair, his
close ally, and Mr Jack Cunningham re-emerged as a potential candidate.
Mrs Margaret Beckett, the deputy leader, was also said to have put off a
decision on whether to stand until after the European parliament election on
June 9.
Aides of Mr Brown, the shadow chancellor, said he was being urged to stand
by union officials concerned about the media bandwagon building up behind Mr
Blair, the shadow home secretary.
Friends of the men had earlier indicated that one of the two would stand
down to avoid blurring the so-called 'modernist' message to which both
subscribe.
Mr Brown's friends said, however, he believed it would be possible for both
to stand without damaging their friendship.
Mr Brown is expected to proceed only if it appears that his support among
constituency members and trade-union levy payers is significantly stronger
than Mr Blair's.
Most MPs said Mr Brown's position appeared untenable, given the strong
support within the parliamentary party for Mr Blair.
Others said the outcome would be uncertain if several candidates decided to
take advantage of the preferential voting system to stand.
Mr Cunningham, shadow foreign secretary, was said to be thinking of standing
if he could rely on the support of about 60 MPs.
</TEXT>
