<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 94 / MPs warn on rising cost of US missiles
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE CLARK, Defence Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain should speed up its purchases of US nuclear missiles for Trident
submarines because the cost may rise sharply, the Commons defence committee
warned yesterday.
The government has so far ordered 44 of the missiles and has said it will
buy about 24 more over the next four to six years.
The committee, in a report on the Trident programme, warns that the unit
cost of missiles sold to Britain will rise sharply if the US administration
scales back its own procurement of the missile.
While the government had already increased its estimate for missile costs by
Pounds 80m, this could prove insufficient if this summer's US Budget calls
for a reduction of missile purchases by the US Navy, and the price
consequently rises.
'We fear that future (price) rises may far exceed provision, and consider
that the Ministry of Defence must be prepared to complete its missile
procurement programme as soon as possible to avoid such cost penalties,' the
report said.
The committee welcomes the fact that estimates for the total cost of the
Trident programme have inched downwards for the eighth successive year - by
Pounds 24m to Pounds 9.94bn. Some Pounds 6.9bn of this money had been spent
by November last year.
However, it expresses disappointment at the low share of sub-contracting
work being awarded to British groups. As of last autumn, UK companies had
won only Pounds 207m worth of business as a result of the Trident programme,
while US groups had obtained orders worth Pounds 3.5bn from Britain.
The committee says many elements in the Trident programme remain subject to
sharp fluctuations in cost, and warns that there must be 'no lessening of
strict control over all areas'.
Trident Programme. HMSO. Pounds 14.60
</TEXT>
