<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 94 / Lecturers walk out over contracts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
More than 800 lecturers went on strike yesterday at Sheffield College, the
country's largest further education college, as the dispute over
government-backed 'flexible' contracts escalated, John Authers writes.
Mr Tim Boswell, the further education minister, has withheld Pounds 50m from
college budgets until the new contracts are introduced. The government
believes the contracts are necessary if the growing demand for flexible
training courses is to be met.
Members of the Natfhe lecturers' union at Sheffield College, which has more
than 850 lecturers on six different sites, plan to strike for a total of
five days. The lecturers say the new contracts include no limits on working
hours.
Ms Sue Berryman, Natfhe negotiating secretary, said union branches at more
than 100 colleges were holding strike ballots and predicted that most would
lead to strike action next month.
Two other unions with fewer members in the sector, the Association of
Teachers and Lecturers and the Association of College Management, have
agreed to the contracts, which offer a one-off payment of Pounds 500 for
longer hours and a 50 per cent cut in holidays.
</TEXT>
