FT  18 MAY 94 / Measured response to Sinn Fein expected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government was last night preparing a deadpan response to the latest
attempt by Sinn Fein, the IRA's political arm, to secure clarification of
the Downing Street Declaration.
Mr John Major met senior ministers including Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign
secretary, and Sir Patrick Mayhew, Northern Ireland secretary, to consider
draft comments understood to do no more than restate existing policy.
The government is expected to publish its commentary, along with Sinn Fein's
questions, today or tomorrow.
The government has come under pressure from unionists and some Conservative
backbenchers not to say anything that might be interpreted as opening
negotiations with republican leaders.
Ministerial aides have been playing down expectations at Westminster,
pointing out that many of the questions raised matters that could be
resolved only in talks between Ulster's constitutional parties.
As the cycle of violence in the province continued with the shootings of two
workmen in north Belfast, Mr Gerry Adams, the Sinn Fein president, seemed to
pave the way for a negative response from republicans.
'There has been growing concern among many nationalists that the British
government may squander yet another opportunity to advance the peace
process,' he said.
Yesterday's killings by loyalist gunmen brought to 28 the total of murders
this year in Northern Ireland.
