<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 94 / BBC strikes start next week
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Unions at the BBC yesterday announced a schedule of two strikes a week
starting from next Tuesday in an increasingly bitter dispute over pay and
conditions.
Tuesday's planned strike of technicians and journalists will last 24 hours,
although subsequent strikes will last for varying periods - some could be
for as little as 10 minutes.
Live radio and television programmes such as news, current affairs and sport
are expected to be the worst affected. The unions said there would be
strikes on June 10, the day after polling in the European elections and
parliamentary by-elections, and June 12, when counting begins for the
European elections.
The BBC's management last night began drawing up contingency plans for
emergency coverage.
The dispute is over plans to introduce performance-related pay and to end
comprehensive collective bargaining and conditions of employment.
Mr Tony Lennon, president of Bectu, the BBC technical union, said his
members had sweated to keep programmes going since the introduction of an
internal market at the corporation, and now the management 'wants blood'.
Ms Margaret Salmon, the BBC's director of personnel, said she was
disappointed at the call for action. The management had wanted to continue
talks, she added. 'We are prepared to talk as soon as the unions are
prepared to talk too.'
</TEXT>
