<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 94 / Fed acts decisively to lift confidence: Bond surge reflects
hopes of end to 'water torture'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the US Federal Reserve, yesterday gave
financial markets most of what they have been demanding for weeks.
Under his leadership, the Fed raised the federal funds rate by a half point
to 4.25 per cent - a more decisive move than the three previous
quarter-point increases announced since February. And, equally important, it
put the increase in context by saying that yesterday's action 'substantially
removes the degree of monetary accomodation which prevailed throughout
1993.'
This was interpreted by some analysts as meaning that the Fed had all but
achieved its immediate goal of raising rates to a 'neutral' level - in other
words, a level consistent with non-inflationary growth in the medium term.
Part of yesterday's surge in bond prices probably reflected hopes that the
policy of repeated incremental increases in short rates - known
disparagingly as 'water torture' - has been put on hold, at least for the
time being.
Given an underlying inflation rate of about 3 per cent, short-term interest
rates of 4.25 per cent imply real or inflation-adjusted rates of about 1.25
per cent. This is within the 1-2 per cent range that most economists would
argue represents a neutral level of real rates in the longer term.
However, it does not imply that the Fed's work is anywhere near complete.
If the economy continues to grow faster than its long-run potential - which
is probably 2.5-3.0 per cent a year - the Fed will want to move beyond
neutrality to an overtly contractionary stance. This would require further
substantial increases in rates, perhaps to well above 5 per cent.
Recent better than expected inflation data - such as April figures for
consumer and producer prices - have led some analysts to conclude that a
further tightening of monetary policy will not be required for several
months. This may be so, but other factors are less encouraging.
The Fed may well conclude more aggressive efforts are needed to prevent the
economy hitting capacity constraints, threatening higher inflation in 1995
and beyond.
The annualised rate of growth admittedly dipped in the first quarter to an
estimated 2.6 per cent against 7 per cent in the fourth quarter. A few
recent indicators have been slightly weaker than expected: retail sales fell
in April after strong upward revisions in February and March; housing starts
also dropped last month, prompting speculation that residential construction
has peaked.
But the preponderance of data still suggest the expansion is uncomfortably
strong. The first quarter figures were distorted by severe winter weather
and an erratically large decline in government spending. The monthly payroll
employment figures give a better indication of underlying trends. In the
first four months, average monthly gains averaged more than 250,000 against
about 200,000 in the fourth quarter of last year and about 160,000 in the
first three quarters of last year.
These figures suggest the economy is still rapidly using up spare industrial
capacity. Last month capacity utilisation in manufacturing industry was 83.0
per cent against 80.6 per cent a year ago and a long-term average of 81.9
per cent. The jobless rate for adults is now 5.6 per cent, close to the
level at which upward pressure on wages has emerged in the past.
Signs that leading European economies are beginning to emerge from recession
will only increase the Fed's fear about a possible overheating of the
domestic economy.
Until now a widening trade account has acted as a brake on US growth. But a
concerted global economic revival could lead to stronger upward pressure on
prices and strengthen the case for prudent US monetary policies.
A second concern for the Fed is the apparent lack of confidence in US
economic policies in financial markets. This is reflected, for example, in
the comparative weakness of the dollar even though interest rates are rising
in the US and falling elsewhere. A portfolio shift out of a currency when
interest differentials are moving in its favour is usually a tell-tale sign
of lack of confidence in economic fundamentals. Yesterday there was no rush
to buy dollars following the Fed's announcement of higher interest rates.
The recent very sharp rise in US long bond yields is also disturbing. A
steepening of the yield curve typically reflects fears of higher inflation
in the future - in other words, a fear that monetary policy is too loose.
With the benefit of hindsight many economists now argue that the Fed should
have begun tightening soooner in this economic cycle - before long bond
yields started rising last autumn.
The Fed doubtless hopes that yesterday's half-point increase in rates will
bolster confidence and lead to a sustained reduction in long yields. But
winning back confidence once it has been eroded is never easy.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
