<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 94 / Unions fear Orly competition
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Air Inter, the French domestic airline, was brought to a virtual standstill
yesterday as unions launched a one-day strike in protest over the
liberalisation of the French airline market. Unions said the introduction of
competition on some of their most profitable routes would compound the
financial pressures facing the loss-making airline. They demanded that Air
Inter be given greater management autonomy from Air France, its state-owned
parent company, and be allowed to operate on profitable European routes.
Last month, the European Commission ordered the French government to open
routes between London and Orly airport in Paris to competition, and said the
lucrative Orly-Toulouse and Orly-Marseilles routes must be opened to rivals
within six months. Mr Michel Bernard, president of Air Inter, said the
relationship between Air Inter and Air France would be reorganised during
the summer. An airline official said it was important the domestic airline
remained part of the Air France group, but increased competition on some of
its profitable routes should be compensated by a relaxation in requirements
to serve unprofitable routessuch as between Paris and Quimper, in Brittany.
</TEXT>
