<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAY 94 / Ministers poised to agree Post Office sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is poised to press ahead with the sale of 51 per cent of
Royal Mail and Parcelforce, ending months of speculation about the Post
Office's future.
The plan - under which Post Office Counters, which runs 19,000 sub-post
offices, would remain in public hands - has emerged as the front runner
among a series of options to be discussed by senior cabinet ministers
tomorrow.
A decision to proceed with the sale, which has been billed as the last big
privatisation, could raise up to Pounds 2bn, probably via a share issue, but
would be certain to unleash a political storm.
Last night opposition politicians, union leaders and some Tory backbenchers
opposed such a move. Even Lady Thatcher baulked at privatising the Royal
Mail in 1987 when she was prime minister.
By devising a compromise short of outright privatisation the government
hopes to win over the large number of Tory MPs who have expressed concern
about the impact of a sale on Britain's rural post office network. The plan
is understood to take account of extensive consultations between Mr Michael
Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, and Conservative backbenchers,
during the government's 22-month Post Office review.
There is a possibility ministers may delay a final decision until later in
the year on the grounds that more public consultation is needed. Some
ministers would prefer to limit the sale to 49 per cent of the Post Office's
letters and parcels arms.
The Conservative party's manifesto for the 1992 general election commits it
to maintaining a nationwide network of post offices and a universal delivery
service within a uniform price structure.
Senior Post Office executives have been keen for some time to proceed with a
partial privatisation, partly to facilitate the organisation's access to
private finance. Earlier this month, Mr Bill Cockburn, chief executive,
revealed that the organisation had made a record operating profit last year.
Mr Alan Johnson, general secretary of the Union of Communication Workers
said last night the proposal meant Britain could 'wave goodbye' to the best
Post Office in the world. He predicted it would mean 'electoral suicide' for
the government.
Mr Nicholas Winterton, the Conservative MP for Macclesfield, said he would
not support the measure unless given a '100-per cent guarantee' that the
government would hold on to its remaining 49 per cent stake.
</TEXT>
