<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAY 94 / International Company News: Air Products covers loss on
derivatives
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Air Products and Chemicals, the US industrial gases group which last week
took a Dollars 60m after-tax charge in its second quarter to cover losses on
five derivatives contracts, said yesterday it would absorb an additional
Dollars 9m charge in the next quarter to cover the cost of closing out the
contracts.
The Pennsylvania-based group said it terminated the interest rate swap
contracts to reduce the company's earnings exposure to fluctuations in
interest rates.
Air Products is the fourth US company to take a charge against its earnings
this year because of problems with derivatives agreements sold by Bankers
Trust, the New York bank. Procter &amp; Gamble, Gibson Greetings and Mead
Corporation incurred losses with contracts bought from Bankers Trust.
The bank last week said it sold derivatives to companies so that they could
manage their debt and investment portfolios, and continued to believe the
contracts were useful to clients.
Air Products had decided to stick with the contracts, recalculating their
value at the end of each quarter. But the contracts were leveraged, which
magnified the potential for losses and left Air Products open to the
possibility of losing more money if interest rates continued to rise.
</TEXT>
