<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAY 94 / London 'likely to add 50,000 office jobs'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Central London is likely to see a growth in office employment of between
50,000 and 65,000 jobs by the year 2000, says a report published yesterday.
The growth could generate demand for 10m sq ft of extra office space, St
Quintin, the chartered surveyors, say.
However, the growth in jobs is likely to be less important in generating
demand for offices than the need for City occupiers to change and upgrade
their accommodation. A quarter of City tenants are housed in unrefurbished
buildings built before 1970.
The projections are based on the assumption that London retains its position
as Europe's leading financial centre. However, it highlights a number of
threats to that position, including increased teleworking and competition
from other centres such as Frankfurt.
Mr Peter Damesick, head of research at St Quintin, emphasised the
uncertainties involved in making long-term projections. 'Even the modest
increase in occupied floor space in our projections is not guaranteed,' he
said.
Prospects for Office Demand. St Quintin Research Department, 33 Cavendish
Square, London W1M 9HF. Pounds 20.
</TEXT>
