<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAY 94 / Asian bank tries to reverse closure
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A director of Mount Banking, the small Asian-owned bank, yesterday tried to
overturn in the High Court the Banking Appeal Tribunal's decision to uphold
Mount's closure by the Bank of England in 1992.
In its first ever case, the tribunal found last October that the Bank had
been right to assess Mount's two directors and shareholders as not 'fit and
proper' to run a bank.
Counsel for Mr Navinchandra Bhagwanji Shah claimed that many of the original
grounds for the Bank's decision had not been upheld by the tribunal and that
it had changed the charges from 'not fit and proper' to 'may not have been
fit and proper'.
Mr Suresh Bhagwanji Shah, the other director and owner of the bank, did not
appeal against the tribunal's decision. The hearing is expected to last
about three days.
</TEXT>
